  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes. These typically include:\n\n1. Requirements for financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\n2. In the United States, key laws include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n\n3. International standards set by:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- United Nations conventions\n- Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n\n4. Typical legal consequences for money laundering include:\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial financial penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential imprisonment\n\n5. Specific prohibited activities:\n- Concealing the source of funds\n- Transferring illegally obtained money\n- Structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n\nThese laws aim to disrupt criminal financial networks and prevent illegal funds from entering the legitimate financial system.",
